# Ansible: Host Variables and Group Variables

## 📌 Overview

In Ansible, variables are used to manage configuration across hosts.  
There are two main types:

- **Host Variables**
- **Group Variables**

---

## 🔹 Host Variables

Host variables are defined for a **specific host**.

### ✅ Use Case
- When each server needs different configuration

### ✅ Example (Inventory)

```ini
[dev]
172.31.34.185 ansible_user=ubuntu env=dev app_port=8080


🔹 Group Variables

Group variables are defined for a group of hosts.

✅ Use Case
When multiple servers share common configuration


✅ Example (Inventory)

[dev]
172.31.34.185
172.31.34.186

[dev:vars]
ansible_user=ubuntu
app_port=8080
env=development

### Applies to all hosts in dev group


Best Practice: Using group_vars and host_vars
📁 Directory Structure
/etc/ansible/
│
├── hosts
├── group_vars/
│   └── dev.yml
├── host_vars/
│   └── 172.31.34.185.yml



✅ group_vars/dev.yml
app_name: myapp
app_port: 8080
env: development

👉 Applies to all hosts in dev

✅ host_vars/172.31.34.185.yml
app_port: 9090

👉 Overrides group variable for this host

⚡ Variable Precedence
Host Variables > Group Variables

👉 Host variables override group variables if conflict occurs

🔹 Playbook Example
- hosts: dev
  become: yes
  tasks:
    - name: Print variables
      debug:
        msg: "App {{ app_name }} running on port {{ app_port }}"
🧪 Output Example

For host 172.31.34.185:

App myapp running on port 9090
🎯 Interview Answer

Host variables are used for host-specific configurations, while group variables are used for common configurations across a group of hosts. Host variables have higher precedence than group variables.